annotatable.link_title: Sweet Child O’ Mine by Guns N’ Roses
annotatable.title: Sweet Child O' Mine

children: The song has three instrumental breaks increasing in length after each chorus with the third elaborate solo being the most notable.
In an effort to make the song more marketable to radio stations, the song was shortened with much of Slash’s guitar solos removed.
Axl loathed the radio edit
, telling Rolling Stone in 1989:

I hate the edit of “Sweet Child O' Mine”… My favorite part of the song is Slash’s slow solo; it’s the heaviest part for me. There’s no reason for it to be missing except to create more space for commercials, so the radio-station owners can get more advertising dollars.

children: The now-famous intro, once chosen as the best riff of all time,
started as Slash was “fucking around with this stupid little riff,” which caught Axl Rose’s attention. Within five minutes, the band had worked Slash’s cyclical riff into the bare bones of a song.
Slash
told some more about the riff
to
Rolling Stone
It’s a combination of influences. From
Jeff Beck
Cream
and

Manfred Mann’s
version of
“Blinded By The Light”
and
Gerry Rafferty’s
“Baker Street.”

annotatable.link_title: Sweet Child O’ Mine by Guns N’ Roses
annotatable.title: Sweet Child O' Mine

children: This guitar solo is widely known as the best guitar solo in history. In fact, this came in on
Rolling Stones as the greatest guitar solo ever.
Apparently, however,
Slash didn’t feel same-way:

When “Sweet Child O’ Mine” was written, it was a joke as far as I was concerned. I was just fuckin’ around when I came up with that riff. To me it was a nightmare because, for some strange reason, everyone picked up on it and, the next thing you knew, it had turned into a song. I hated it forever! The guitar solo itself is a one-take, spontaneous kind of thing. Having played the song at rehearsals enough times, when it came to recording it I knew exactly where the melody was and it came real easy.

annotatable.link_title: Sweet Child O’ Mine by Guns N’ Roses
annotatable.title: Sweet Child O' Mine

children: According to Slash’s autobiography, producer
Spencer Proffer

suggested adding a dramatic breakdown before the ending. No one had any idea what to do. As they listened again and again to the song in the control room, Axl started asking “Where do we go? Where do we go now?… where do we go?.” Spencer turned down the music, and said, “Why don’t you just try singing that?” and thus the last part of the song was born.

annotatable.link_title: Sweet Child O’ Mine by Guns N’ Roses
annotatable.title: Sweet Child O' Mine

children: Sweet Child O’ Mine isn’t just a made up term of endearment for the sake of writing a love song.
Axl Rose
used similar pet names like Sweet Child in letters he wrote to his girlfriend at the time Erin Everly, which were later auctioned off:

An adult person calling their partner “child” is kind of odd years after the song’s release. It’s mostly fallen out of favor, but at the time it wasn’t much different than something like “baby,” which was done then and is more common now, and was not exclusive to Guns N’ Roses. There are several love songs from around the same time that use similar terms, like
“Starry Eyes”
from Mötley Crüe, one of the band’s influences:
Okay child, you’ve had to take the pain of a man in the streets

annotatable.link_title: Sweet Child O’ Mine by Guns N’ Roses
annotatable.title: Sweet Child O' Mine

children: Axl, like many song writers before him, takes parts of his lover’s body and compares them to other things. In this case, her hair evokes a childhood memory—namely, of a place where a child scared of the storm outside hides until it’s clear.
Axl had a painful childhood where he would get beaten and his sister would get raped. So here he’s referring to the place he hid away from all that.

He sees his childhood sweetheart, his first love around and about and it takes him straight back to where they used to ‘hang out’ together and what would his life be like if he was still with her and if he stares too long he thinks he would have been happier so he can feel the tears building up so he has to look away to keep his composure.

annotatable.link_title: Sweet Child O’ Mine by Guns N’ Roses
annotatable.title: Sweet Child O' Mine

children: When he thinks of her smile it reminds him of the time in his life where he was happy and everything was good. The child-like smile is the intuition of all human. We lost it in the cruel egoistic society. The girl’s smile reminds him of the instinct of pure happiness, just like “fresh sky.”
Axl Rose
had a traumatic childhood and suffered from
molestation and abuse.
This line is especially significant as it symbolizes how her smile reminds him of the few joyful childhood memories he has.
